nt in the "Great Game" in the early twentieth century, its submission to Chinese Communist rule in the 1950s, and the troubled times of recent decades.Tibet sheds light on the country's complex relationship with China and explains often-misunderstood aspects of its culture, such as reborn lamas, monasteries and hermits, The Tibetan Book of the Dead, and the role of the Dalai Lama. Van Schaik works through the layers of history and myth to create a compelling narrative, one that offers readers a greater understanding of this important and controversial corner of the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300172171423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300172171.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles